    <h1>Take a tour of hid&#xAD;den Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore |</h1>
    <h2>From bee&#xAD;keep&#xAD;ing to how funeral par&#xAD;lours work, My Com&#xAD;mu&#xAD;nity Fes&#xAD;ti&#xAD;val&#x2019;s tours take you be&#xAD;hind the scenes of in&#xAD;dus&#xAD;tries, faiths and homes</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201124/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-24"><time>2020-11-24</time></a>
        - <span>FRONT PAGE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Clara Lock&#xD;&#xA;Travel Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent</span>
    </section>

    <p>Drop into a funeral par­lour at mid­night, find out how your mail is sorted at SingPost Dis­tri­bu­tion Cen­tre, go on a tour of Ah Hua Ke­long and visit one of Sin­ga­pore’s last joss stick mak­ers.</p>
    <p>Do all this and more at the up­com­ing My Com­mu­nity Fes­ti­val, which will show­case a se­ries of tours that high­lights lo­cal her­itage sto­ries.</p>
    <p>The in­au­gu­ral fes­ti­val, which is on from Dec 4 to 20, is held by My Com­mu­nity, a non-profit or­gan­i­sa­tion that has been run­ning her­itage tours in his­toric neigh­bour­hoods such as Queen­stown and Tiong Bahru since it was founded in 2010.</p>
    <p>This year’s fes­ti­val was a nat­u­ral pro­gres­sion, say the or­gan­is­ers, as they have al­ways wanted to show­case sto­ries from other less­fre­quented neigh­bour­hoods.</p>
    <p>The fes­ti­val had been slated for April this year, but had to be post­poned due to the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>Events fall into one of six cat­e­gories, in­clud­ing Makan My Curry, in which 11 home cooks from var­i­ous back­grounds will wel­come vis­i­tors into their homes and show­case much-loved fam­ily recipes.</p>
    <p>Af­ter Hours @ My Com­mu­nity gives vis­i­tors a peek at what goes on af­ter dark, in­clud­ing a walk through Gey­lang’s red light dis­trict and a glimpse into for­eign worker dor­mi­to­ries in the area.</p>
    <p>There are also tours of fac­to­ries, small busi­nesses run by tra­di­tional crafts­men, cof­fee roast­ers, cafes and places of wor­ship, in­clud­ing those of lesser-known re­li­gions like the Baha’i faith.</p>
    <p>There are 45 in-per­son events, with mul­ti­ple runs of each. There will also be one vir­tual tour of Paci­ficLight Power Sta­tion in Jurong.</p>
    <p>Fes­ti­val di­rec­tor Kwek Li Yong, 30, who is also the ex­ec­u­tive di­rec­tor and co-founder of My Com­mu­nity, says these tours are a chance for people to delve deeper into sto­ries around them.</p>
    <p>“We want to nar­rate the en­dur­ing sto­ries of com­mon people, help people get to know their neigh­bours a bit bet­ter and build a more re­silient so­ci­ety,” he says.</p>
    <p>The Straits Times pre­views three tours worth check­ing out.</p>
    <p>claral@sph.com.sg</p>
    <p>For more in­for­ma­tion, go to my­commu­ni­tyfes­ti­val.sg.</p>
    <p>This is part of an oc­ca­sional se­ries on lo­cal tours. For more sto­ries on ex­plor­ing Sin­ga­pore, go to str.sg/sg-go-where.</p>

